/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>To limit non-specific epitope binding. All ABs have specificity.  Washing is usually trying to remove weaker binding to non-intended targets.<\/li>\n<li>For flow, excess AB that is not bound, if also pre-conjugated to a fluorophore, may allow for excitation of the fluorophore while going through flow even though the antibody isn't bound to the cell type of interest.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>If you had a very specific AB, and very little excess, you may not notice a thing. I'm sure there are additional reasons; these are the two that immediately come to mind based on my own flow cytometry experiments.<\/p>\n","answer_id":39910,"question_id":39547,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39547/purpose-of-antibody-wash","last_activity_date":1445713523,"creation_date":1444748344,"answer_count":1,"title":"Purpose of antibody wash","body":"<p>It is common practice after surface staining cells for flow cytometry analysis to wash the antibody out of solution before analyzing a sample. I have tried analysis with and without washing the antibody out and notice no significant difference by flow. So is there a reason people do this step that maybe I'm just not noticing?<\/p>\n","question_id":39547,"tags":["cell-biology","antibody","flow-cytometry"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":39910,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":59,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49adeab5651d99d0cc9b43e11cad2fd1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19544,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19544/stareagle130","reputation":23,"display_name":"stareagle130"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.co