 movement, loss of jaw bone can occur around the implant.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>However, Professor Sharpe identified the following obstacle:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>What is required is the identification of adult sources of human epithelial and mesenchymal cells that can be obtained in sufficient numbers to make biotooth formation a viable alternative to dental implants.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>For some background, consult <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2100358/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Biological tooth replacement (2006; Sartaj, Sharpe)<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Unfortunately the 2013 article was the last I heard of it - possibly for the aforementioned reason. If you're really interested, you might consider attempting to contact Professor Sharpe yourself.<\/p>\n","answer_id":39685,"question_id":39656,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39656/what-makes-diffculty-to-make-a-human-bio-tooth-compare-to-a-mouses","last_activity_date":1445609528,"creation_date":1445003216,"answer_count":2,"title":"What makes diffculty to make a human bio-tooth compare to a mouse's?","body":"<p>Some time ago I read a news article that said a bio-engineered tooth based on a mouse's would be available around 2015. There was some research about it at King's College in the UK, and many other institutes.<\/p>\n\n<p>Now, I haven't heard any news that such a thing is available. It seems to be a basic result of stem-cell research, how much difference can there be between a human's tooth and a mouse's?<\/p>\n","question_id":39656,"tags":["human-biology","stem-cells","biomedical-engineering"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"primarily opinion-based","is_answered":false,"view_count":191,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1445609528},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8b42fbbdb4edd12ce424b6a3e02acabd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19601,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/