rong>partition coefficient<\/strong> will give you some insight on how fast molecules will pass through membrane, if at all.<\/p>\n\n<p>Good luck on the searching!<\/p>\n\n<p>@ Ro Siv - Simple diffusion is not facilitated diffusion<\/p>\n","answer_id":39832,"question_id":39829,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39829/how-is-the-concept-of-simple-diffusion-possible","last_activity_date":1445481320,"creation_date":1445469668,"answer_count":1,"title":"How is the Concept of Simple Diffusion Possible","body":"<p>How can a substance pass through a lipid membrane in a cell through simple diffusion? In order for something to be able to go through the membrane, in simple diffusion, it must be hydrophobic, or non polar. The reason for this is that in order for it to easily interact and pass the fatty acid part of the lipid membrane, which is hydrophobic or non polar, it must also be hydrophobic and non polar. But in order for this substance to pass the phosphate part of the membrane, which is hydrophilic, or polar, doesn't it also need to be polar and hydrophilic?<\/p>\n","question_id":39829,"tags":["cell-membrane","lipids"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":39,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Kyg92.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6061,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6061/rhill45","reputation":2493,"display_name":"rhill45","accept_rate":79},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":0,"post_id":36738,"edited":false,"creation_date":1439223055,"comment_id":61410,"body":"People cannot change their fingerprints. It is possible to temporarily remove enough of the pattern to make the fingerprint useless for identification, but nothing more. No