or alignment.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>bwa mem -M sequence.fa seq_0_1.fq seq_0_2.fq &gt; P0.sam \n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now, I check the ASCII of base quality (column 11 in the SAM format, the specification is <a href=\"https://samtools.github.io/hts-specs/SAMv1.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>head -n 3 P0.sam | cut -f11\n\nIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIII\nIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIII\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>According to this <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FASTQ_format\" rel=\"nofollow\">page<\/a>, the ASCII (in order of quality) is:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>!\"#$%&amp;'()*+,-./0123456789:;&lt;=&gt;?@ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ[\\]^_`abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz{|}~\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><strong>Question<\/strong>: My experiment is supposed to be perfect, so my base-quality metrics are expected to appear near the right-end of the list (like x,y,z). However, my metric I is no-where near the top of the list. In particular, I'm unable to achieve anything from J to ~. Why?<\/p>\n","question_id":39813,"tags":["bioinformatics"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":39814,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":35,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1445405659},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/85e6d848d3c7bf5ed0bb0717974bf07d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13238,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13238/yehosef","reputation":369,"display_name":"Yehosef","accept_rate":83},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hXPhP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12923,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12923/alec-djinn","reputation":647,"display_name":"alec_djinn"},"score":0,"post_id":34507,"edited":false,"creation_date":1432508270,"comment_id":55434,"body":"An even more minimalistic approach would use a single molecule to do the enzymatic job while storing evolvable informations. In this case RNA alone has been proposed as substitute for proteins and DNA in a very minimal cell. In theory also DNA alone could do the same. However the minimal tasks needed to be done: maintain the self (to be compartimentalized), to grow (to have a flux of molecule not in equilibrium), to divide, to maintain the information stably enough to be useful for the next generation and at the same time prone too mutability to evolve."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hXPhP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12923,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12923/alec-djinn","reputation":647,"display_name":"alec_djinn"},"score":0,"post_id":34507,"edited":false,"creation_date":1432508603,"comment_id":55435,"body":"So to make cells from scratch you would need: amphiphilic molecules to form a membrane, a decent mix of simple molecules (sugars, nucleic acids, peptides) that serve as reactant and building blocks for more complex things, some simple catalyzer (metals, minerals, pepetides, aptamers, etc..) to run the reactions, enough energy to maintain lots of reactions running and keep them far from the equilibrium. Of course, lots of time..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/85e6d848d3c7bf5ed0bb0717974bf07d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13238,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13238/yehosef","reputation":369,"display_name":"Yehosef","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":34507,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hXPhP.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12923,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12923/alec-djinn","reputation":647,"display_name":"alec_djinn"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1432509762,"comment_id":55436,"body":"@alec_djinn - could add you comments as an answer so I could upvote them?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,