:{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":0,"post_id":21299,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410711941,"comment_id":33447,"body":"Assuming no bias, do you think that 1) spiders construct their webs where there is a source of heat because they have evolved in order to construct their webs in these places (as warm temperature attract insects) (you seemed to say no but I am not sure) 2) spiders construct their webs all over but those that are poorly located die 3) spiders construct their webs all over but when they starve they move 4) spiders observe spots of high insect concentration before constructing their web. All of these explanations would explain why there are more webs in the light."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/F00PM.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8517,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8517/mike-taylor","reputation":5784,"display_name":"Mike Taylor"},"score":0,"post_id":21299,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"edited":false,"creation_date":1410715776,"comment_id":33449,"body":"@Remi.b I made no assumptions. I took the question solely at face value. You and Oreotrephes are correct about the potential for visual bias. My hypothetical example was based on spiders building near lights because insects are attracted to light. Your hypotheses are testable but I&#39;m skeptical about whether spiders can scout out spots of high concentration in advance of web building. It&#39;s also possible some spider species are themselves attracted to light but benefit from the insect concentration."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"http