ode and against the running direction of the DNA. Some of the EtBr will intercalate into the double helix and stain it (although weaker the further the DNA migrates), the rest migrates as long as the power is on. This is why it is usually recommended to stain gels which run very long afterwards, as this increases the staining."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1b3c5b025ca581db5a8fdd2564b5367c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6511,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6511/bez","reputation":2430,"display_name":"Bez"},"score":0,"post_id":23884,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1415656700,"comment_id":37830,"body":"@Chris Ah, but I was told it is the pH effect that causes this since in my apparatus containing old running buffer this is worse than when made freshly and when I use the buffer in the positive chamber side of the apparatus and sock in EtBr, it doesn&#39;t stain. But I could be wrong! I can edit my response if thats best?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":23884,"edited":false,"creation_date":1415657062,"comment_id":37832,"body":"No, the pH has almost no effect on this. You will loose conductivity in older buffers as well when it heats up, so the migration is not working that good anymore. You could add EtBr also to the lower buffer reservoir, but this can get messy."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1b3c5b025ca581db5a8fdd2564b5367c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6511,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6511/bez","reputation":2430,"display_name":"Bez"},"score":1,"post_id":23884,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1415657155,"comment_id":37833,"body":"@Chris ah interesting! thanks! I shall edit my response!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1445356456,"creation_date":1415654176,"body":"<p>As you can see from the bottom of the gel, the brightness of the bands have reduced even for the DNA ladder/marker. The main reason for this is that when you are running an agarose gel containing EtBr, due to the positive charge of the EtBr, the stain runs to the negative chamber, against the direction of the DNA migration as @Chris has pointed out! Although some of the DNA will stain but the rest of the EtBr will migrate towards the top of the gel (where the DNA is loaded).<\/p>\n\n<p>A quick remedy for this is once you ran your gel is to soak your gel in a separate container containing your stain and running buffer such as TAE. I do this for one hour and that makes a huge difference!! Also make sure you regularly change the buffer in your agarose gel running apparatus and don't use the same buffer for a long time since again as @Chris has correctly pointed out there is a reduced conductivity in the older buffers when they heat up so migration does not work as well! Obviously this response assumes that you have a good degree (amount) of DNA in your gel bands, which can be calculated by nanodrop once you extracted the DNA using an extraction kit, or whatever method you normally use. I hope this helps!<\/p>\n\n<p>This answer is more suited to the title of the question since after reading the main question a bit more carefully I'm slightly confused! So do you see anything at all or your product is far too faint? could you tell us where on the gel, relative to the ladder you expect to see this band? are they the ones at the button of the gel, below the loading buffer?<\/p>\n","answer_id":23884,"question_id":23881,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1445356456}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/23881/how-can-i-get-brighter-dna-bands","last_activity_date":1445356456,"creation_date":1415650130,"answer_count":1,"title":"How can I get brighter DNA bands?","body":"<p>I amplified my DNA with real time PCR. The amplification curve shows good amplification but not a single band is observed in my gel after gel electrophoresis. What would be the possible reasons? <\/p>\n\n<p>I am attaching a photograph of my gel below. My ladder opened correctly but not a single band can be observed:<\/p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/wJPau.jpg\" alt=\"Gel\"><\/p>\n","question_id":23881,"tags":["gel-electrophoresis","biotechnology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":526,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1415688670},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0a145d1a6d27b0f3a16b4b0d4e2a245f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5349,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5349/thi","reputation":14,"display_name":"thi"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0348be8a2ca783679f79cd6b0754da14?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4140,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4140/j-alfred-prufrock","reputation":651,"display_name":"J. Alfred Prufrock"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1389219743,"creation_date":1389219743,"body":"<p>Sulfonamides competitively inhibit the enzyme dihydropteroate synthase, which is involved in the tetrahydrofolate synthesis pathway in most bacteria. Rickettsia lack this enzyme target, and thus possess a natural resistance to the antibiotic. As tetrahydrofolate is an essential compound, it is believed that Rickettsia possess an alternative enzymatic process which is not susceptible to sulfonamides, or the bacteria simply acquire the compound (or its immediate precursors) from their environment.<\/p>\n","answer_id":14348,"question_id":14318,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c09b03ce9a3f7a5771db0d4f6b50fe33?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19522,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19522/angel","reputation":11,"display_name":"angel"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1445353392,"creation_date":1445353392,"body":"<p>richettsiae lacks folP gene which encodes for dihydropteroate synthase and folA which encodes dihydrofolate reductase enzymes. This shows that richettsiae lacks the target of sulfonilamides. therefore sulfonilamides are ineffective to inhibit its growth and thus if given may lead to increased mortility and morbildity.<\/p>\n\n<p>reference:http:escholarship.org<\/p>\n","answer_id":39798,"question_id":14318,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/14318/why-does-sulfonamid-not-inhibit-the-growth-of-rickettsia","last_activity_date":1445353392,"creation_date":1389105401,"answer_count":2,"title":"Why does sulfonamid not inhibit the growth of Rickettsia?","body":"<p>Sulfonamid is an antimicrobial agent, why has it no effect on the growth of Rickettsia?<\/p>\n","question_id":14318,"tags":["microbiology"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":202,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1389105987},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/YDmUK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11866,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11866/sidney","reputation":123,"display_name":"Sidney"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39796/why-would-the-addition-of-whey-protein-to-oatmeal-make-the-oatmeal-more-runny","last_activity_date":1445349089,"creation_date":1445349089,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why would the addition of whey protein to oatmeal make the oatmeal more runny?","body":"<p>So, at the suggestion of a friend I added some protein to my morning oatmeal. While I do feel better for it, I noticed a few things it did to the oatmeal I didn't expect, the primary is that the addition of powder to a pre-measured amount of oats and water made the oatmeal runnier than normal. I assumed the addition of more dry material would make it thicker than normal. What sort of interactions does the addition of protein cause here?<\/p>\n\n<p>(I had considered posting this on the physical fitness forum, but I'm assuming the answer is really more about the bio-chemistry and interaction of the protein)<\/p>\n","question_id":39796,"tags":["proteins"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":22,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZBeuU.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9020,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9020/look-behind-you","reputation":808,"display_name":"Look behind you","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/oGTOv.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15499,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15499/bodhi-zazen","reputation":136,"display_name":"bodhi.zazen"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1445347328,"creation_date":1429972136,"body":"<p>Muscle growth and development is mediated by \"trophic factors\" not biochemical reactions (ATP) or muscle contraction directly. The best method of releasing tropic factors is exercise and not electrical stimulation or biochemical reactions (ATP) or biomechanical contraction.<\/p>\n\n<p>Nerve ending release growth or tropic factors which stimulate muscle growth and for example if the nerves die off either due to injury or disease (ALS) the muscles will atrophy.<\/p>\n\n<p>Not all of the tropic factors are as of yet unknown, but it is these tropic factors that stimulate muscle growth not the biochemical or biomechanical reaction of the muscle (contraction). One can not as of yet stimulate muscle growth by delivering electrical entegy to the muscle for example (it has been tried to in an effort to maintain muscle mass in critically ill patients).<\/p>\n\n<p>There is a review of the trophic factors here - <a href=\"http://neuromuscular.wustl.edu/lab/trophic.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://neuromuscular.wustl.edu/lab/trophic.htm<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>And a review of electrical stimulation - <a href=\"http://www.medword.com/MedwordStore/PCP/EMS_truth.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.medword.com/MedwordStore/PCP/EMS_truth.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>There are many claims of benefit for electrical stimulation, such as regeneration of the facial nerve in facial paralysis, such as bells palsy.<\/p>\n\n<p>The \"problem\" is that the prognosis in bells palsy is very good, even without electrical stimulation, and so it is difficult to \"prove\" benefit with electrical stimulation<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>With or without treatment, most individuals begin to get better within 2 weeks after the initial onset of symptoms and most recover completely, returning to normal function within 3 to 6 months.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.ninds.nih.gov/disorders/bells/detail_bells.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ninds.nih.gov/disorders/bells/detail_bells.htm<\/a><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Statistically, the natural history without treatment was described in a study of 1011 patients in 1982 [8]. One-third had an incomplete paralysis, and two-thirds had complete paralysis. Overall, 85 percent showed signs of recovery within three weeks, 71 percent had complete recovery, 13 percent had slight sequelae, and 16 percent had residual weakness, synkinesis and/or contracture. Patients with incomplete lesions had a 94 percent rate of return to normal function, while only 60 percent of those with clinically complete lesions returned to normal function. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":31711,"question_id":31701,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1445347328}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31701/what-is-the-connection-between-exercise-and-muscle-growth","last_activity_date":1445347328,"creation_date":1429927722,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the connection between exercise and muscle growth","body":"<p>From a physiological perspective, all that is done during exercise is the expending of energy in the form of ATP to fuel muscle contraction and extension.<\/p>\n\n<p>When I looked up why muscle grow due to exercise, there is the claim that recovery of micro lesions formed during exercise enables slight growth of muscle. I am not sure how micro lesions are formed and intuitively, these micro lesions should cause atrophy of the muscle rather than strengthening of the muscle fibers. <\/p>\n\n<p>Further there is no logical connection as to why muscle fibers would be strengthened rather than just restored to its previous form during rest.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can someone help me make the mental leap from the consumption of ATP through exercise to muscle growth? <\/p>\n","question_id":31701,"tags":["muscles"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":31711,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":112,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/04dpm.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8129,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8129/matas-vaitkevicius","reputation":263,"display_name":"Matas Vaitkevicius","accept_rate":71},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"ht