your last sentence <code>Why<\/code>) refers to. Maybe both. In such case, why would you expect that a common mechanism explains both observations? You should probably restrict your question to one or the other only. <\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>For these above reasons, the question cannot be correctly answered in its above form. But below is something that may already help you.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Birth defects<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>It is true that birth defects is more prevalent among males than among females (in humans). According to <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11745830\" rel=\"nofollow\">Lary and Paulozzi 2001<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The overall prevalence of major defects at birth was 3.9% among males and 2.8% among females.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Reading their abstract only, one can see that they go on saying<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Defects of the sex organs were eight and one-half times more prevalent among males and accounted for about half of the increased risk of birth defects among males relative to females. Urinary tract defects were 62% more prevalent among males, and gastrointestinal tract defects were 55% more prevalent among males.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>In consequence, it seems at first sight that the difference in birth defects frequency is very much related to the development of sex organs. In their abstract they announce that they discuss the mechanisms that account for such difference.<\/p>\n\n<p>I currently don't have access to the paper (I am not on campus) to report more details of their findings.<\/p>\n","answer_id":39744,"question_id":39743,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1445315170},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e5f813565669b0b078c9e7b5d4172b0f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19454,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19454/atp","reputation":320,"display_name":"ATP"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date"