ural-of-octopus\">here<\/a> for a nice discussion."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":0,"post_id":6949,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445230245,"comment_id":66631,"body":"We might get some insight by asking what&#39;s special about SIX legs or TEN. No vertebrate has more than two pairs of legs, of course. But, as far as I know, all insects have six legs, while most arachnids have eight. Centipedes and millipedes have far more, though I don&#39;t think they&#39;re technically defined as legs. In short, it doesn&#39;t make sense for an animal to have more legs than it needs for survival. Apparently, the laws of physics make three or four pairs of legs an optimum for really tiny creatures with exoskeletons, while vertebrates get by with just four legs. I don&#39;t believe cephalopods"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e8d0828732c8eb54a0335e7eab1ec9f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":112,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/112/michael-kuhn","reputation":3583,"display_name":"Michael Kuhn","accept_rate":75},"score":6,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d68656858083f23c2808393402d0152e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1858,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1858/paul-a-clayton","reputation":312,"display_name":"Paul A. Clayton"},"score":2,"post_id":6951,"edited":false,"creation_date":1359413031,"comment_id":8514,"body":"The question asked about animals with 360 degree motion."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d5e8817011bf40f20c518af3c0dc7187?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":137,"link":"http://biology.stacke