rrection. I nonchalantly wrote sister chromatids instead of homologous chromosome."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1445232047,"creation_date":1444888222,"body":"<p>A progeny is not a half clone of its parents.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Each cell expresses both maternal and paternal genes. There are no parts of the body or even a cell for that matter that is identical to one of the parents. <\/li>\n<li>When haploid gametes form, chromosomes are randomly segregated. So the gamete receives either paternal and maternal chromosomes (grandparents of the progeny) randomly. This technically means that the gamete is not an exact half of the parent's genome. <\/li>\n<li>During gameteogenesis (production of sperm/ovum), genetic recombination happens between nonsister chromatids of homologous chromosomes (meiotic crossover). This mechanism creates a small shuffle in the haploid genome that the gamete is carrying.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":39611,"question_id":39609,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1445232047}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39609/are-progenies-factually-half-clones-of-the-parents","last_activity_date":1445232047,"creation_date":1444887167,"answer_count":1,"title":"Are progenies factually half-clones of the parents?","body":"<p>Given that a \"clone\" (if anything, in the context of human cloning) is taken to be, as far as I have understood, a specimen possessing the same genome as his \"father/mother\", aren't all \"non-cloned\" organisms born out of inter-individual, heterosexual reproduction (i.e. \"standard\" sons and daughters), effectively \"half-clones\", under that same definition?*<\/p>\n\n<p>Are \"normal\" sons and daughters \"half-clones\", as a matter of fact?<\/p>\n","question_id":39609,"tags":["human-biology","genetics","reproduction","cloning"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":58,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1444900974},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/zGsne.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9111,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9111/thinly-veiled-question-mark","reputation":189,"display_name":"thinly veiled question mark"},"closed_date":1445232519,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39756/why-do-i-wake-up-with-morning-wood","last_activity_date":1445231533,"creation_date":1445231533,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why do I wake up with morning wood?","body":"<p>According to this <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/a/5196/9111\">answer on a question about the brain<\/a>, the answer implies that based on certain activities the human body is undergoing, the brain then diverts the appropriate needed resources to help in that action, for example diverting blood flow to the muscles when exercising, or when eating food, diverting blood to the stomach.<\/p>\n\n<p>That said, when I wake up and have a raging hard-on, for no apparent reason, I am still quite perplexed and wonder I wake up with \"morning wood\", so to speak.  I'm not aroused when I wake up, I sometimes take bathroom breaks in the middle of the night but I still get morning wood regardless of if or when I take breaks, and I'm trying to understand why the body would divert so much blood flow to an area which isn't exactly \"working\" or \"active\" in any sense.   <\/p>\n\n<p>Could anyone explain why morning wood occurs? Is it something to do with how we sleep or something to do with dreaming? Is there a reason why the body directs blood so much to your groin in the morning as opposed to anything else?<\/p>\n","question_id":39756,"tags":["human-biology","human-anatomy"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"duplicate","is_answered":false,"view_count":12,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/20d873baa75c66bdcf8d06512ee664cc?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17085,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17085/mousomer","reputation":138,"display_name":"m