cts with their living environment. <\/p>\n\n<p>My point is mainly that sociality (in general or in felines in particular) is not either/or for a particular species, and other felines also show social behaviours and sometimes form groups (so sociality should be viewed as a sliding scale). Granted, lions are definitely the feline with the strongest social behaviors, and they form the largest social groups. It is therefore interesting to think about why that is the case, and what group dynamics and tradeoffs that determine the social behaviours of lions.<\/p>\n","answer_id":36613,"question_id":36560,"up_vote_count":9},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6c84049f4c143434586b155b0d58b385?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":5311,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5311/sanalphatau","reputation":84,"display_name":"Sanalphatau"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1439584788,"creation_date":1439584788,"body":"<p>I agree with some comments that have been made on the validity of the wording used by OP. However there is a legitimate thrust to the question. What could drive Lion sociality? <\/p>\n\n<p>Females are the base unit of lion social groups. Males are generally the nomadic sex. Male lions will try to take over a group of females by killing the current cubs and mating with the females. By having groups of females they can drive off males that are not related to their offspring.<\/p>\n\n<p>Males are equally rewarded for banding together to defend females and to subdue larger groups of females or other bands of males. Lion packs are therefore formed by these antagonistic interaction between male and female lions. More research is needed!<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/000334729580157X\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/000334729580157X<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":36853,"question_id":36560,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d1c6641d5c8556d9f351765c89b510f6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19493,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19493/david-blomstrom","reputation":1247,"display_name":"David Blomstrom"},"score":0,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/210cc4a4b2f281aaffe0b26521fe1ab8?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1590,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1590/rg255","reputation":11513,"display_name":"rg255","accept_rate":66},"score":0,"post_id":39755,"edited":false,"creation_date":1457422150,"comment_id":76531,"body":"Please could you add some supporting scientific material that reinforces your answer and allows further reading."}],"down_vote_count":2,"last_activity_date":1445230654,"creation_date":1445230654,"body":"<p>I can offer a guess or two...<\/p>\n\n<p>First, cats are primarily ambush hunters that are generally associated with forests. Many are semi-arboreal.<\/p>\n\n<p>Lions generally live in open savannas and grasslands. If you stop and think about it, the animals they prey on - grassland ungulates - are social species that live in herds, whereas forest-dwelling ungulates (e.g. the okapi and bongo) are often solitary.<\/p>\n\n<p>Also, lions typically prey on big animals, and they may benefit from greater numbers in subduing their prey (though more solitary tigers also prey on large animals).<\/p>\n\n<p>Another possibility is that lion prides have value in defense from other predators (or possibly even prey, such as buffalo). Leopards can drag their prey into the safety of trees, while cheetahs are stuck on the ground - and they're notorious for losing hard-won prey to other predators.<\/p>\n","answer_id":39755,"question_id":36560,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/36560/why-are-lions-the-only-social-cats","last_activity_date":1445230654,"creation_date":1438506116,"answer_count":3,"title":"Why are lions the only social cats?","body":"<p>We know that almost all cats are solitary. \nHow did the Lions (<em>Panthera leo<\/em>) end up social animals? Do we have an explanatory evolutionary path describing how the Lions became social while the rest of the felines remained solitary?<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm not asking what general rules apply to evolution, but, rather - what evolutionary path has led to <strong>this specific outcome<\/strong>. \nI know a bit of evolutionary game theory. No need to reiterate the obvious. I'm asking if we know the mechanism or the evolutionary pressure in this particular case.<\/p>\n","question_id":36560,"tags":["evolution","zoology","sociality","feline"],"score":7,"accepted_answer_id":39755,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":647,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1438680423},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/06b0c88bb86cb532fc94663c6a566a0c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":827,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/827/octern","reputation":418,"display_name":"octern"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":31352,"edited":false,"creation_date":1432983066,"comment_id":55932,"body":"The topic is immensely interesting, but this question is too complex for me to answer. A very nice, concise and informative review is freely accessed here: <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12081851\" rel=\"nofollow\">ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12081851<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XdJ9g.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19432,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19432/akadrhouse","reputation":448,"display_name":"akaDrHouse"},"score":3,"is_accepted":f